<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1920-06-01T16:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1920-06-01T16:00:00-05:00" n="273" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d273">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">812.51/579: Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to
                                the Chargé in Mexico</hi> (<persName type="to"><hi rend="italic">Summerlin</hi></persName>)</head>
                        <opener><seg rendition="#center">[Paraphrase]</seg></opener>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1920-06-01T17:00:00-04:00"><hi rend="italic">June 1,
                                        1920—5 p.m.</hi></date></dateline></opener>
                        <p>162. Embassy’s telegram dated May 22, 1920, 4 p.m. Banks in New York City
                            which carry accounts of National Railways, Comision Monetaria, and
                            Financial Agent, Government of Mexico, have notified the Department that
                            they will not honor any checks which may be drawn on said accounts until
                            Government now functioning in Mexico is recognized.</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Colby</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
